<exercises xml:id="s_matrixreps_ex">
  <exercisegroup>
    <title></title>
    <introduction>
    Compute <m>[T]_B^{B'}</m> for each provided <m>T\colon V\rightarrow W</m> and choice of bases <m>B</m> and <m>B'</m> of <m>V</m> and <m>W</m>. You may assume that the given <m>T</m> is a linear transformation.
    </introduction>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>T\colon P_3\rightarrow P_4</m>, <m>T(p(x))=p'(x)-x\, p(x)</m>; <m>B=(x^3, x^2, x, 1)</m>; <m>B'=(x^4, x^3, x^2, x,1)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>T\colon P_2\rightarrow M_{22}</m>, <m>T(p(x))=\begin{bmatrix}
            p(-1)\amp p(0)\\
            p(1)\amp p(2)
          \end{bmatrix}</m>; <m>B=(x^2,x,1)</m>; <m>B'=(E_{11}, E_{12}, E_{21}, E_{22})</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>T\colon \R^2\rightarrow \R^2</m>, <m>T=T_A</m> where <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}
            1\amp 2\\ 2\amp 4
          \end{bmatrix}</m>; <m>B=B'=\left((1,2),(2,4)\right)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T\colon P^3\rightarrow P^2</m> is a linear transformation with matrix representation
        <me>
          [T]_B^{B'}=\begin{bmatrix}
            2\amp 0\amp 0\amp -1\\
            0\amp 1\amp -1\amp 0\\
            1\amp 1\amp 1\amp 1
        \end{bmatrix}
        </me>,
        where <m>B=(x^3, x^2, x, 1)</m> and <m>B'=(x^2, x, 1)</m>. Use the defining property <xref ref="eq_matrixrep_prop"/> of <m>[T]_B^{B'}</m> to determine the formula for <m>T(ax^3+bx^2+cx+d)</m> for an arbitrary polynomial <m>ax^3+bx^2+cx+d\in P_3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>T\colon \R^2\rightarrow \R^2</m> is a linear transformation with matrix representation
        <me>
          [T]_{B}=\begin{bmatrix}
          1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 2
        \end{bmatrix}
        </me>,
        where <m>B=\left( (1,2), (-1,1)\right)</m>
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use the defining property <xref ref="eq_matrixrep_prop"/> of <m>[T]_B</m> to compute <m>T((1,0))</m> and <m>T((0,1))</m>. (You will first need to compute <m>[(1,0)]_B</m> and <m>[(0,1)]_B</m>. )
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use (a) and the fact that <m>T</m> is linear to give a general formula for <m>T(x,y)</m> in terms of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
    </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The function <m>S\colon M_{22}\rightarrow M_{22}</m> defined as <m>S(A)=A^T-A</m> is a linear transformation.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>C=[S]_B</m>, where <m>B</m> is the standard basis of <m>M_{22}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="th_matrixreps_model"/> to lift bases of <m>\NS C</m> and <m>\CS C</m> back to bases for <m>\NS S</m> and <m>\im S</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Identify <m>\NS S</m> and <m>\im S</m> as familiar subspaces of matrices.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The function <m>T\colon P_2\rightarrow P_3</m> defined by <m>T(p(x))=xp(x-3)</m> is a linear transformation.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>A=[T]_B^{B'}</m>, where <m>B</m> and <m>B'</m> are the standard bases of <m>P_2</m> and <m>P_3</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="th_matrixreps_model"/> to lift bases of <m>\NS A</m> and <m>\CS A</m> back to bases for <m>\NS T</m> and <m>\im T</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>

</exercise>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>T\colon \R^2\rightarrow \R^3</m> be the linear transformation defined as <m>T(x,y)=(x-y, x+2y, y)</m>, and let <m>B=\left((1,0), (0,1)\right)</m>, <m>B'=\left((1,1),(1,-1)\right)</m>, <m>B''=\left((1,0,0),(0,1,0),(0,0,1)\right)</m>
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute <m>[T]_B^{B''}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute <m>[T]_{B'}^{B''}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

</exercise>


  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T\colon P_2\rightarrow M_{22}</m> be the linear transformation defined as
        <me>
          T(p(x))=\begin{bmatrix} p(0)\amp p(1)\\ p(-1)\amp p(0) \end{bmatrix}
        </me>,
        and let  <m>B=(1,x,x^2)</m>, <m>B'=(1, 1+x, 1+x^2)</m>, <m>B''=(E_{11}, E_{12}, E_{21}, E_{22})</m> (the standard basis of <m>M_{22}</m>).
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>[T]_B^{B''}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Compute <m>[T]_{B'}^{B''}</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>

  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>T_1\colon V\rightarrow W</m> and <m>T_2\colon W\rightarrow U</m> be linear transformations, and suppose <m>B, B', B''</m> are ordered bases for <m>V</m>, <m>W</m>, and <m>U</m>, respectively. Prove:
        <me>
          [T_2\circ T_1]_B^{B''}=[T_2]_{B'}^{B''}[T_1]_B^{B'}
        </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Let <m>A_1=[T_1]_B^{B'}</m> and <m>A_2=[T_2]_{B'}^{B''}</m>. Show that the matrix <m>A_2A_1</m> satisfies the defining property of <m>[T_2\circ T_1]_{B}^{B''}</m>: <ie />,
        <me>
          A_2A_1[\boldv]_B=[T_2\circ T_1(\boldv)]_{B''}
        </me>
        for all <m>\boldv\in V</m>.

      </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>


</exercises>
